Hi @lisaciso ,

The root cause for this is that `Source` method to edit message body in TinyMCE editor is available and it should be removed:

{F1388140}

However, if that's not the case, here's my proposed solution which solves reported vulnerability: 
I am not going to open issue in concrete5 GitHub repo to not to alarm potential attackers about this problem. This Gist's visibility is set to private:

https://gist.github.com/bl4de/770ef2e145625f6aafe9af669e5662dd

### Solution

There is an additional `sanitizeXSSVectors()` method in `Editor` class (`concrete/src/Conversation/Editor/Editor.php`), which is called in line 264:


```php
public function formatConversationMessageBody($cnv, $cnvMessageBody, $config = array())
    {
        /** @var  \Concrete\Core\Html\Service\Html $htmlHelper */
        $htmlHelper = Core::make('helper/html');
        $cnvMessageBody = $htmlHelper->noFollowHref($cnvMessageBody);
        if (isset($config['htmlawed'])) {
            $default = array('safe' => 1, 'elements' => 'p, br, strong, em, strike, a');
            $conf = array_merge($default, (array) $config['htmlawed']);
            $result = htmLawed($cnvMessageBody, $conf);
        } else {
            $result = $cnvMessageBody;
        }
        if (isset($config['mention']) && $config['mention'] !== false) {
            $users = $cnv->getConversationMessageUsers();
            $needle = array();
            $haystack = array();
            foreach ($users as $user) {
                $needle[] = "@" . $user->getUserName();
                $haystack[] = "<a href='" . $user->getUserPublicProfileURL() . "'>'@" . $user->getUserName() . "</a>";
            }

            $result = str_ireplace($needle, $haystack, $result);
        }
        // Replace any potential XSS
        $result = $this->removeJavascriptLinks($result);
        $result = $this->sanitizeXSSVectors($result);    // line 264
        return $result;
    }
```

### Implementation

`sanitizeXSSVectors()` method recursively sanitize message body removing potential XSS vectors. I've tested it against several potential payloads and it seems to work fine, however no XSS protection is ever 100% bulletproof ;) Even Google couldn't kill XSS via Chrome's XSS Auditor, so no doubt I won't be able to do this :D


```php
/**
     * Protects against potential XSS attacks vectors
     * 
     * There are only a handful methods of executing inline JavaScript
     * in HTML code: <script> tag, javascript: pseudoprotocol (already sanitized
     * by removeJavascriptLinks()), event handlers and tags which can embed
     * external JavaScript (svg, iframe, object).
     * 
     * To remove any potential XSS vactors created by methods above, some kind
     * of sanitization of conversation message body has to be performed.
     * 
     * Proposed solution is definitely not the ideal one and will need further
     * refactoring and reviewing, but some initial tests I did shows effectiveness
     * against most of simple, popular XSS vectors
     * 
     *
     * @param string $html
     * @return string
     */
    protected function sanitizeXSSVectors($html)
    {
        // List of tags we do not want to see in the conversation message body
        // Depends on further needs, this list can be adjusted
        $dangerousTags = array(
            '/<script|\/script>/im',
            '/<iframe|\/iframe>/im',
            '/<object|\/object>/im',
            '/<svg/im',
        );

        // recursively remove all potential dangerous HTML tag(s):
        foreach ($dangerousTags as $tag) {
            while (preg_match($tag, $html)) {
                $html = preg_replace($tag, '', $html);
            }
        }

        // Recursively removes inline JavaScript events handlers
        $eventHandlerRe = '/on[a-z].+=[\(\'"`a-z].+[\'"`\)]/im';
        while (preg_match($eventHandlerRe, $html)) {
            $html = preg_replace($eventHandlerRe, '', $html);
        }

        // returns sanitized message body
        return $html;
    }
```

### Summary

The method is called in both Frontend and Admin panel.
